===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bere|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|bera|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*berô}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|bear|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|beer|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Bär|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|bjørn|lang=da}}).

{{rel-top|etymology notes}}
This is generally taken to be from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰer-||shining, brown}} (compare [[Tocharian]] A {{term||parno}}, B {{term||perne|radiant, luminous}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|bė́ras||brown|lang=lt}}), related to {{term|brown|lang=en}} and {{term|beaver|lang=en}}.

Germanic replaced the older name of the bear, [[Appendix:Proto-Indo-European/h₂ŕ̥tḱos|*rtko-]] with the epithet "brown one", presumably due to taboo avoidance; compare Russian {{term|медведь||bear|lang=ru}}, literally “honey-eater”.

However, Ringe (2006:106) doubts the existence of a root  *bʰer- meaning "brown" ("an actual PIE word of [the requisite] shape and meaning is not recoverable") and suggesting that a derivation from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*ǵʰwer-||wild animal}} "should therefore perhaps be preferred", implying a Germanic merger of  ''*ǵʰw'' and ''*gʷʰ''  (''*gʷʰ'' results in Germanic ''*b'' regularly, e.g. in ''[[Appendix:Proto-Germanic/bidjaną|*bidjaną]]'')
